{"cursor":"82966","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox\n| title=Milky Way Galaxy image= caption=An image of the Milky Way's Galactic\n| Center in the night sky above Paranal Observatory titlestyle=background:\n| #30D5C8lc; headerstyle=background: belowstyle=background: #30D5C8;\n| labelstyle=background: inherit; header1=Observation data label2=Type\n| data2=SBc (barred spiral galaxy) label3=Diameter\n| data3= label4=Thickness data4=\n| label6=Number of stars data6=\n| label7=Oldest known star data7=13.2 Gyr label8=Mass\n| data8=1.0â1.5 M â label9=Sun's\n| distance to Galactic Center data9= label10=Sun's\n| Galactic rotation period data10=200 Myr (negative rotation) label11=Spiral pattern rotation period data11=50 Myr label12=Bar pattern rotation period\n| data12=15â18 Myr label13=Speed relative to CMB\n| rest frame data13= below=See also: Galaxy, List of\n| galaxies\n}}\n\nThe 'Milky Way' is the galaxy that contains our Solar System. This name derives from its appearance as a dim \"milky\" glowing band\narching across the night sky, in which the naked eye cannot distinguish\nindividual stars. The term \"Milky Way\" is a translation of the Classical Latin\nvia lactea, from the Hellenistic Greek Î³Î±Î»Î±Î¾Î¯Î±Ï ÎºÏÎºÎ»Î¿Ï (pr. galaxÃ­as kÃ½klos,\n\"milky circle\"). The Milky Way appears like a band because it is a disk-shaped\nstructure being viewed from inside. The fact that this faint band of light is\nmade up of stars was proven in 1610 when Galileo Galilei used his telescope to\nresolve it into individual stars. In the 1920s, observations by astronomer Edwin\nHubble showed that the Milky Way is just one of many galaxies.\n\nThe Milky Way is a barred spiral galaxy 100,000â120,000 light-years in diameter\ncontaining 200â400 billion stars. It may contain at least as many planets. The Solar System is\nlocated within the disk, around two thirds of the way out from the Galactic\nCenter, on the inner edge of a spiral-shaped concentration of gas and dust\ncalled the Orion Arm. The stars in the inner â10,000 light-years are organized\nin a bulge and one or more bars. The very center is marked by an intense radio\nsource named Sagittarius A* which is likely to be a supermassive black hole.\nStars and gas throughout the Galaxy rotate about the center at approximately the\nsame speed, which contradicts the laws of Keplerian dynamics. This indicates\nthat much of the mass of the Milky Way does not emit or absorb electromagnetic\nradiation; this mass is known as dark matter. The\nrotational period is about 200 million years at the position of the Sun. [http://books.google.com/books?id=U4FZp6f6q6MC&pg=PA45&lpg=PA45&dq=m-\nilky+way+galaxy+rotates+million+years&source=bl&ots=SRXBmYOdEV&sig=ggVcW5IBX4zm-\nvJbmT86_towlCR0&hl=en&sa=X&ei=MREIUKOGJofa0QHs4aGOBA&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&-\nq=milky%20way%20galaxy%20rotates%20million%20years&f=false Gunter Faure, Teresa\nM. Mensing, Introduction to Planetary Science: The Geological Perspective, page\n45] The Galaxy as a whole is moving at a velocity of 552 to 630 km\nper second, depending on the relative frame of reference. It is estimated to be\nabout 13.2 billion years old, nearly as old as the Universe. Surrounded by\nseveral smaller satellite galaxies, the Milky Way is part of the Local Group of\ngalaxies, which forms a subcomponent of the Virgo Supercluster.\n","linknr":1690,"url":"Milky_Way","recorded":1362371870,"links":214,"instances":["astronomy","constellation","constellation","constellation","astronomy","astronomer","constellation","astronomy","astronomy_and_astrology","constellation","astronomy","constellation","satellite","astronomy","dwarf_galaxy","ratio","constellation","constellation"],"pdf":["http://www.astro.caltech.edu/~george/ay20/Chiappini-MilkyWay.pdf"],"categories":["Milky Way Galaxy|","Milky Way Subgroup","Local Group","Galactic astronomy","Barred spiral galaxies","Spiral galaxies"],"headings":["Appearance","Size and composition","S